[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m-
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m-- Update to version 4.0.0 , important changes
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m- * The special files /dev/pid, /dev/ppid, /dev/pgrpid and /dev/user are
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m-    now completely gone. Use PROCINFO instead.
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m- * The POSIX 2008 behavior for `sub' and `gsub' are now the default.
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m- * In POSIX mode, string comparisons use strcoll/wcscoll.
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m- * Gawk now treats ranges of the form [d-h] as if they were in the C
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m-
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m-
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m--------------------------------------------------------------------
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m-Tue Apr 19 13:46:32 CEST 2011 - dmueller@suse.de
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m-
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m-- update to 3.1.8:
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m-  * The zero flag no longer applies to %c and %s; apparently the standards
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m-  changed at some point.
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m-  * Failure to open a socket is no longer a fatal error.
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m-  * dfa.h and dfa.c are now more-or-less in sync with GNU grep, for the first
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m-  time in many years.
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m-  * Gawk no longer includes its own copy of libsigsegv but it will use it if
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m-  installed on the build system. The --disable-libsigsegv configure option
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m-  is now gone.
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m-  * The ' flag (%'d) is now just ignored on systems that can't support it.
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m-  * Gawk now has support for z/OS (IBM S/390 architecture).
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m-  * Gawk now handles multibyte strings better in [s]printf with field
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m-   widths and such.
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m-  * A getline from a directory is no longer fatal; instead it returns -1.
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m-  * Per POSIX, special variable names (like FS) cannot be used as function
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m-   parameter names.
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m-  * The new -O / --optimize option enables simple constant folding on
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m-  the parse tree during parsing.  We hope that with time the number
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m-  of optimizations will increase.
[0m[31m[TOOL][0m [31m-  * Lots of bug fixes, see the ChangeLog.
